05419nam a22006615i 9780822379157DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19991999ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223791577 a10.1515/97808223791572doi  a(DE-B1597)554257  a(OCoLC)1226678885  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0170002bisacsh04a7912211 aHanson, Ellis, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOut Takes :bEssays on Queer Theory and Film /cEllis Hanson. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1999] 4c©1999  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b55 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSeries Q00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Out Takes -- tCRUISE CONTROL Rethinking Masculinity in Classic Cinema -- tQueering the Deal: On the Road with Hope and Crosby -- tThe Queer Aesthete, the Diva, and The Red Shoes -- tRear Window's Glasshole -- tVisual Pleasure in 1959 -- tLESBIAN LOOKS Desire, Identification, Fantasy -- tCassandra's Eyes -- t"That Ain't All She Ain't": Doris Day and Queer Performativity -- tLesbians Who Bite -- tHeavenly Creatures in Godzone -- tQUEERING THE REEL Sexual Politics and Independent Cinema -- tWhite Neurotics, Black Primitives, and the Queer Matrix of Borderline -- tScandalous l Kenneth Anger and the Prohibitions of Hollywood History -- tQueer Period: Derek Jarman's Renaissance -- tForbidden Love: Pulp as Lesbian History -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis collection brings together the work of both film scholars and queer theorists to advance a more sophisticated notion of queer film criticism. While the "politics of representation" has been the focus of much previous gay and lesbian film criticism, the contributors to Out Takes employ the approaches of queer theory to move beyond conventional readings and to reexamine aspects of the cinematic gaze in relation to queer desire and spectatorship.The essays examine a wide array of films, including Calamity Jane, Rear Window, The Hunger, Heavenly Creatures, and Bound , and discuss such figures as Doris Day, Elizabeth Taylor, and Alfred Hitchcock. Divided into three sections, the first part reconsiders the construction of masculinity and male homoerotic desire-especially with respect to the role of women-in classic cinema of the 1940s and 1950s. The second section offers a deconstructive consideration of lesbian film spectatorship and lesbian representation. Part three looks at the historical trajectory of independent queer cinema, including works by H.D., Kenneth Anger, and Derek Jarman.By exploring new approaches to the study of sexuality in film, Out Takes will be useful to scholars in gay and lesbian studies, queer theory, and cinema studies.Contributors. Bonnie Burns, Steven Cohan, Alexander Doty, Lee Edelman, Michelle Elleray, Jim Ellis, Ellis Hanson, D. A. Miller, Eric Savoy, Matthew Tinkcom, Amy Villarejo, Jean Walton  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Lesbian Studies.2bisacsh1 aDoty, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVillarejo, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Bonnie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, D. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanson, Ellis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSavoy, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWalton, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllis, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdelma